The game's art direction, world, and exploration are all great. Really enjoyed the game it's just the fact it's built upon frustrating fights is a bit of a grievance. Then pair with PC version running like poop ain't great either.

Godrick, a good real fight. 
Renala, a Fools Idol prelude then a real fight.
Rykard, Yhorm but 2 health bars
Morgott a real fight
Malenia, Life steal on every hit on a fast-attacking enemy.
Radahn, a Berserk reference and a "siege" fight 
Mohg, a mmo life steal mechanic

Game designed around frustrating the player with a lot of double trouble boss fights of enemies, having 3-8 strings of attacks that can lead into either another 4 swings or a chaser if one hits you and you back off to heal.

After beating Elden Ring, my opinion of the game is a very good game with a whole lot of frustrating mechanics, technical problems, and somewhat disappointing fights. For at least the Great Rune fights.

The good parts about it are the visual design, the music is great, especially during stealth portions when you're being searched for or found out. I'd give Sekiro a 7/10. It's not awful but how quickly it dials up bullshit in mid to late game sucked all fun out of it for me.

So, to sum it up. Mechanically, it's  fine, but feels unfinished and way too hard in the games favor. It's poorly designed with enemy placement, and the amount of abilities bosses can do, along with broken hitboxes where most things hit with a huge phantom hitbox.

Sekiro tells you, you're going to die. But, punishes you by taking 1/2 your money and XP each time until you reach the botom of your capped level, and with Dragonrot cutting off NPC questlines till you cure them, which is a finite resource.

Sekiro wants you to play it more thought out, but it punishes you for that by wanting you to be able to do reflex deflections from an enemies forward swing and 4 swing follow up
It wants you to use your tools but the only one that's any good is the firecracker, axe, and Shuriken.

Since you know, that's how difficulty works. Not use the mechanics to create situations you have to adapt to. Nah, just make most enemies swing faster, hit harder, do longer combos, and make them tankier. Sekiro wants you to be aggressive, but punishes you for it.

Alright, so I'm like 3 bosses from beating Sekiro. My thoughts? Up to the first two bosses is great. It's challenging and engaging. Then it swiftly turns from challenging to "How can we overwhelm you while breaking most of our own mechanics in the games favor."
